    System.out.println("File does not exist");
}
<<<explanation>>>: The exists() method of the File class tests whether the file or directory denoted by this abstract pathname exists.


A: Your code for creating a file and writing to it is correct. The error you're getting is because the file you're trying to write to doesn't exist.
The FileNotFoundException is thrown when the File object is trying to open a file that doesn't exist. In your case, you're trying to open a file named "file.txt" in the current directory of your program. If this file doesn't exist, a FileNotFoundException is thrown.
To fix this, you need to make sure that the file "file.txt" exists in the directory you're specifying. You can create the file using the following code:
File file = new File("file.txt");
try {
    if (file.createNewFile()) {
        System.out.println("File created");
    } else {
        System.out.println("File already exists");
    }
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}

This code will create a new file named "file.txt" in the current directory of your program. If the file already exists, it will not be created again and the message "File already exists" will be printed.
Also, make sure that you have the necessary permissions to create files in the directory you're specifying. If you're running your program from Eclipse, you might need to run it as an administrator.

